@NODE Introduction
@TITLE "HotCorner · Introduction"


    @{b}Introduction@{ub}

    HotCorner is a simple commodity that inserts hotkeys in the
    input event chain when the mouse pointer hits a screen corner.

    Each screen corner has its own set of hotkeys: primary and
    secondary events.

    Primary and secondary events are sent each in turn when mouse
    pointer hits a corner. If secondary event is not set, primary
    event is always sent.

    Each event can be delayed before inserting the hotkey in
    the input device chain. This feature can be handy with the top
    right corner (f.ex: hotkey opens a window that overlays the screen
    depth gadget).

    Event turn can be made consistent between screen with 'Keep
    screen state' option. Primary and secondary events working in
    pair like IControl 'Show Window' or 'Hide Window' hotkeys may benefit
    from the 'Keep screen state' option.



@ENDNODE

@NODE Requirements
@TITLE "HotCorner · Requirements"


    @{b}Requirements@{ub}


    o MorphOS 1.4 or better

    o A few KB free RAM

    o A few KB free hard disk space


@ENDNODE

@NODE Installation
@TITLE "HotCorner · Installation"


    @{b}Installation@{ub}


    Copy HotCorner to WBStartup. No installer required.



@ENDNODE

@NODE Startup
@TITLE "HotCorner · Startup"


    @{b}Startup@{ub}


    HotCorner can be launched from Ambient or from the CLI. If HotCorner
    is installed in 'SYS:WBStartup' it will be launched automatically
    at system start.

    HotCorner supports all default MUI and Commodity @{"tooltypes" link ToolType}.


    @{b}CLI@{ub}

    It has no options. Just start it. If the HotCorner icon is not found then
    default values for @{"tooltypes" link ToolType} will be used.


@ENDNODE

@NODE Settings
@TITLE "HotCorner · Settings"


    @{b}Settings@{ub}


    HotCorner settings window is divided in four identical sections. Each
    section is dedicated to a screen corner.


    @{b}Hotkey Settings@{ub}

    HotCorner accepts any valid hotkey combination.

    Only valid hotkey combinaison will work. The field is cleared if the
    provided hotkey is not valid.


    @{b}Delay@{ub}

    Each event has its own delay from 0 ms to 1000 ms. Setting delay to 0 ms
    triggers the hotkey immediately.

    If the hotkey triggers the opening of a window then delaying the hotkey
    event might help to keep the screen bar symbols under the mouse pointer
    accessible.

    Delayed hotkey event abort upon mouse move or click.


    @{b}Keep Screen State@{ub}

    Some hotkeys work in combination. Primary and secondary events might need
    to be kept consistent from screen to screen context.

    'Keep screen state' retains the next event to be triggered for each screen.

    Example: IControl features 'Show windows' and 'Hide windows' hotkeys.
    Primary and secondary event need to be kept consistent between screen
    context.


@ENDNODE

@NODE ToolType
@TITLE "HotCorner · ToolType"


    @{b}Tooltypes@{ub}


    @{b}CX_PRIORITY@{ub}

    Adjusts the priority of the commodity. CX_PRIORITY range
    is -128 to 127. Defaults to 0.


    @{b}CX_POPUP@{ub}

    Tells HotCorner to open its settings window upon startup. Defaults to 'AUTO'.

    'AUTO' tells HotCorner to open its settings window if no preferences are found
    in ENV: or ENVARC:.


    @{b}CX_POPKEY@{ub}

    Opens HotCorner settings window. Defaults to nothing.


@ENDNODE


@NODE FAQ
@TITLE "HotCorner · FAQ"


    @{b}Frequently Asked Question@{ub}


    o Could HotCorner execute a CLI command?

    No. Use another commodity to handle that part. HotCorner is meant to send
    hotkeys in the input device chain when mouse pointer hits screen corners.


    o Why did you write HotCorner?

    I wrote HotCorner because reaching Ambient desktop icons is annoying when
    lots of windows are open and blocking the view.

    IControl has some hotkey to show/hide windows that are handy but hitting
    a screen corner with the mouse pointer might be faster.


    o Is it an Exposé like?

    No. Absolutely not. HotCorner doesn't do any windows management.  It just
    adds hotkeys events in the input event chain.

    IControl offers hotkeys for window management though and they can be
    utilized in HotCorner.



@ENDNODE


